# WHAT IT IS
#   ZSA Technology Labs ships the **Moonlander Mark I**, **Voyager**,
#   and **ErgoDox EZ** — three of the most influential ergonomic
#   split-keyboards on the market, used by professional programmers,
#   writers, designers, and accessibility-needs users worldwide.
#   Each ZSA keyboard supports:
#
#     • Per-key RGB LED backlighting (Moonlander: 76 keys; Voyager:
#       52 keys; ErgoDox EZ: 76 keys)
#     • Multi-layer keymap system (up to 32 layers per keymap,
#       with momentary / toggle / one-shot / tap-dance layer
#       activation)
#     • Status LEDs (4 amber LEDs on Moonlander + Voyager
#       indicating which layer is active)
#     • Custom QMK-based firmware compiled via Oryx (ZSA's web
#       editor) and flashed via the Wally Flasher app
#     • The Keymapp companion app — a desktop application that
#       talks to the keyboard over its CDC (Communications Device
#       Class) USB endpoint and exposes the keyboard state to
#       any gRPC client on the host machine
#
#   `kontroll` is the canonical command-line gRPC client for
#   Keymapp's API.  It lets users + automation scripts:
#
#     • Query the connection status of every ZSA keyboard on
#       the host
#     • Connect to a specific keyboard by friendly-name index
#       (or to the first detected one via `connect-any`)
#     • Switch the active layer programmatically (`set-layer`)
#     • Set the RGB color of an individual LED (`set-rgb`),
#       all LEDs (`set-rgb-all`), or restore the layer-default
#       LED colors (`restore-rgb-leds`)
#     • Toggle individual status LEDs (`set-status-led`) or
#       restore them all (`restore-status-leds`)
#     • Increase / decrease the per-key brightness in
#       configurable step sizes (`increase-brightness` /
#       `decrease-brightness`)
#
#   The wire protocol between `kontroll` and Keymapp.app is a
#   `tonic`-generated gRPC service definition (`KeyboardService`)
#   over a Unix-domain socket on macOS + Linux (`/tmp/keymapp.sock`
#   by default) or a Windows named-pipe transport.  All requests
#   are typed prost protobuf messages with strict schema
#   validation.
#
# CLI ARGUMENT GRAMMAR  (verbatim from src/cli.rs clap-derive
#                       `Cli` struct + `Commands` enum;  extracted
#                       via raw.githubusercontent.com fetch of
#                       src/cli.rs)
#
#   kontroll [OPTIONS] <COMMAND>
#
#   Global options:
#     -h, --help                     Show help
#     -V, --version                  Print version
#     -p, --port <PORT>              Server socket path (Linux/
#                                    macOS) or port on Windows
#
#   Commands:
#     status [OPTIONS]               Get the status of the
#                                    currently connected keyboard
#         -j, --json                 Output JSON instead of human-
#                                    readable text
#                                    [default: false]
#     list                           List all available keyboards
#     connect -i <INDEX>             Connect to a keyboard by
#                                    index (returned by `list`)
#     connect-any                    Connect to the first keyboard
#                                    detected by Keymapp
#     set-layer -i <INDEX>           Set the layer of the currently
#                                    connected keyboard
#     set-rgb -l <LED> -c <HEX> [-s <SUSTAIN>]
#                                    Set the RGB color of a single
#                                    LED  (color is a hex string
#                                    like `#ff0000`)
#     set-rgb-all -c <HEX> [-s <SUSTAIN>]
#                                    Set the RGB color of all LEDs
#     restore-rgb-leds               Restore the RGB color of all
#                                    LEDs to their default
#     set-status-led -l <LED> [-o] [-s <SUSTAIN>]
#                                    Set / unset a status LED
#         -o, --off                  Turn the status LED off
#                                    (default is to turn it on)
#     restore-status-leds            Restore the status of all
#                                    status LEDs to their default
#     increase-brightness [-s <STEPS>]
#                                    Increase the LED brightness
#                                    [default: 1 step]
#     decrease-brightness [-s <STEPS>]
#                                    Decrease the LED brightness
#                                    [default: 1 step]
#     disconnect                     Disconnect from the currently
#                                    connected keyboard
#
# AXIS / CORPUS POSITION
#   `zsa/kontroll` declares a **direct** dependency on
#   `tonic = "0.11.0"` + `tonic-build = "0.11.0"` (for the
#   build-time protobuf codegen) + `prost = "0.12.4"` in its
#   `Cargo.toml` (verified via `gh api repos/zsa/kontroll/
#   contents/Cargo.toml`).  The `build.rs` script invokes
#   `tonic_build::compile_protos` on the `keymapp.proto` file
#   to generate the typed `KeyboardServiceClient` Rust API
#   that `src/lib.rs` and `src/cli.rs` use.
#
#   `hyperium/tonic` is **THE canonical Rust gRPC library** —
#   the official tonic / Hyper / Tower / Tokio team's
#   reference implementation of the gRPC protocol on the
#   Rust async ecosystem, in continuous active development
#   since 2019 with 11,500+ ★ on GitHub and tens of millions
#   of all-time crates.io downloads.  It is the **only mature
#   pure-Rust gRPC implementation**: alternatives are either
#   thin wrappers around C-language grpc-core (e.g.
#   `grpcio` for the older C++ FFI binding) or feature-
#   limited (e.g. `grpc-rust`).
#
#   tonic ships as a multi-crate workspace:
#
#     • `tonic`                      the runtime — typed
#                                    `Channel::from_static(url)`
#                                    /  `Channel::builder(uri)`
#                                    /  `Server::builder()`
#                                    typed connection
#                                    constructors;  typed
#                                    `Status::ok()` /  `Status::
#                                    cancelled(msg)` /  `Status::
#                                    invalid_argument(msg)` /
#                                    `Status::deadline_exceeded(msg)`
#                                    /  `Status::not_found(msg)`
#                                    /  `Status::already_exists(msg)`
#                                    /  `Status::permission_denied(msg)`
#                                    /  `Status::unauthenticated(msg)`
#                                    /  `Status::failed_precondition(msg)`
#                                    /  `Status::aborted(msg)` /
#                                    `Status::out_of_range(msg)` /
#                                    `Status::unimplemented(msg)` /
#                                    `Status::internal(msg)` /
#                                    `Status::unavailable(msg)` /
#                                    `Status::data_loss(msg)` /
#                                    `Status::resource_exhausted(msg)`
#                                    typed gRPC status-code
#                                    constructors covering all
#                                    16 canonical gRPC status
#                                    codes from RFC 2.0
#     • `tonic-build`                the build-time proto-buffer
#                                    codegen — typed
#                                    `tonic_build::configure()
#                                    .build_client(true)
#                                    .build_server(true)
#                                    .compile(&["proto.file"],
#                                            &["proto_dir"])`
#                                    builder API
#     • `tonic-types`                typed Google.Rpc.Status
#                                    error-details message
#                                    schemas (BadRequest,
#                                    PreconditionFailure, etc.)
#     • `tonic-reflection`           typed gRPC Server Reflection
#                                    Protocol service
#                                    implementation (the
#                                    `grpc.reflection.v1alpha.
#                                    ServerReflection` service
#                                    that grpcurl + grpc-gui +
#                                    Postman + Insomnia use to
#                                    auto-discover service
#                                    schemas at runtime)
#     • `tonic-health`               typed gRPC Health Checking
#                                    Protocol service
#                                    implementation
#                                    (`grpc.health.v1.Health`)
#     • `tonic-web`                  typed gRPC-Web transport
#                                    (browser-compatible gRPC
#                                    over HTTP/1.1 + WebSocket)
#     • `tonic-channel`              typed multi-endpoint channel
#                                    with load-balancing
#
#   Key APIs:
#
#     • `Channel::from_static("http://...")` / `Channel::from_shared(...)`
#       /  `Endpoint::from_shared(url).timeout(d).keep_alive_while_idle(b)
#       .http2_keep_alive_interval(d).http2_adaptive_window(b)
#       .initial_connection_window_size(n).initial_stream_window_size(n)
#       .tcp_nodelay(b).tcp_keepalive(d).tls_config(rustls_or_openssl_config)
#       .connect_lazy()` typed Endpoint builder
